# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: skeletal-animation
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Winsor McCay's *Gertie the Dinosaur* (1914) is often considered the first example of true character animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Later, Otto Messmer imbued Felix the Cat with an instantly recognizable personality during the 1920s.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] In the 1930s, Walt Disney made character animation a particular focus of his animation studio, best showcased in productions such as *Three Little Pigs* (1933), *Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs* (1937), *Pinocchio* (1940), and *Dumbo* (1941).
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] *Snow White and the Seven Dwarfs* was the "first full length animated and musical feature" in Technicolor.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Disney animators such as Bill Tytla, Ub Iwerks, Grim Natwick, Fred Moore, Ward Kimball, Les Clark, John Sibley, Marc Davis, Wolfgang Reitherman, Hal King, Hamilton Luske, Norm Ferguson, Eric Larson, John Lounsbery, Milt Kahl, Frank Thomas and Ollie Johnston all became masters of the technique.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Frank and Ollie, as they were affectionately known by their protégés, taught that the thoughts and emotions behind the character were primary to the creation of every scene.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Out of all the Nine Old Men, Frank and Ollie were the most known for their mentor/apprentice relationships, and the sharing of their knowledge about creating characters, most notably as transcribed through *Disney Animation: The Illusion of Life*.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] This book relays the 12 basic principles of animation, and is informally considered to be the 'animation bible' for any student of animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Character animation is not limited to Hollywood studios, however.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Some of the finest examples of character animation can be found in the work of Nick Park of Aardman Animations and Russian independent animator Yuri Norstein.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Though typical examples of character animation are found in animated feature films, the role of character animation within the gaming industry is rapidly increasing.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Game developers are using more complicated characters that allow the gamer to more fully connect with the gaming experience.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] *Prince of Persia*, *God of War*, *Team Fortress* or *Resident Evil* contain examples of character animation in games.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Character animation is often contrasted with creature animation, in which specialised animators bring to life realistic animals and creatures, such as dinosaurs and fantasy creatures.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Visual effects animators specialise in animating vehicles, machinery, and natural phenomena such as rain, snow, lightning and water, as well as the "non-natural" effects often seen in science fiction films.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] There is a good deal of overlap between these areas.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Sometimes, visual effects animators will use the same principles of character animation; an early example is the pseudopod in *The Abyss*.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] On-going computer science research on character animation deals with the question of generating multi-layer level of detail at run-time to allow large crowd rendering in real-time applications.
[src:skeletal-animation/character-animation] Realistic character movements are often simulated using motion capture and soft-body dynamics simulations.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] The "morph target" is a deformed version of a shape.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] When applied to a human face, for example, the head is first modelled with a neutral expression and a "target deformation" is then created for each other expression.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] When the face is being animated, the animator can then smoothly morph (or "blend") between the base shape and one or several morph targets.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] Typical examples of morph targets used in facial animation are a smiling mouth, a closed eye, and a raised eyebrow.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] Early 3D videogames, such as Quake and Crash Bandicoot use per-vertex animation for all character animations.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] When used for facial animation, these morph targets are often referred to as "key poses".
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] The interpolations between key poses when an animation is being rendered, are typically small and simple transformations of movement, rotation, and scale performed by the 3D software.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] Not all morph target animation has to be done by actually editing vertex positions.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] It is also possible to take vertex positions found in skeletal animation and then use those rendered as morph target animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] An animation composed in one 3D application suite sometimes needs to be transferred to another, as for rendering.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] Because different 3D applications tend to implement bones and other special effects differently, the morph target technique is sometimes used to transfer animations between 3D applications to avoid export issues.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] There are advantages to using morph target animation over skeletal animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] The artist has more control over the movements because they can define the individual positions of the vertices within a keyframe, rather than being constrained by skeletons.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] This can be useful for animating cloth, skin, and facial expressions because it can be difficult to conform those things to the bones that are required for skeletal animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] Vertex animation is usually a lot more labor-intensive than skeletal animation because every vertex position must be manually manipulated and, for this reason, the number of pre-made target morphs is typically limited.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] Also, in methods of rendering where vertices move from position to position in-between frames, a distortion is created that does not happen when using skeletal animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] This is described by critics of the technique as looking "shaky".
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] On the other hand, this distortion may be part of the desired "look".
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] For large models, vertex animation requires significant memory and storage as the position of each modified vertex must be stored for each frame.
[src:skeletal-animation/morph-target-animation] In contrast, skeletal animation requires only the storage of bone transformations for each frame.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In films, television shows and video games, motion capture refers to recording actions of human actors and using that information to animate digital character models in 2D or 3D computer animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] When it includes face and fingers or captures subtle expressions or voices, it is often referred to as **performance capture**.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In many fields, motion capture is sometimes called **motion tracking**, but in filmmaking and games, motion tracking usually refers more to match moving.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In motion capture sessions, movements of one or more actors are sampled many times per second.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Whereas early techniques used images from multiple cameras to calculate 3D positions, often the purpose of motion capture is to record only the movements of the actor, not their visual appearance.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This *animation data* is mapped to a 3D model so that the model performs the same actions as the actor.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This process may be contrasted with the older technique of rotoscoping.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Camera movements can also be motion captured so that a virtual camera in the scene will pan, tilt or dolly around the stage driven by a camera operator while the actor is performing.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] At the same time, the motion capture system can capture the camera and props as well as the actor's performance.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This allows the computer-generated characters, images and sets to have the same perspective as the video images from the camera.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] A computer processes the data and displays the movements of the actor, providing the desired camera positions in terms of objects in the set.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Retroactively obtaining camera movement data from the captured footage is known as *match moving* or *camera tracking*.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The first virtual actor animated by motion-capture was produced in 1993 by Didier Pourcel and his team at Gribouille.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] It involved "cloning" the body and face of French comedian Richard Bohringer, and then animating it with still-nascent motion-capture tools.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] There are many applications of motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The most common are for video games, movies, and movement capture, however there is a research application for this technology being used at Purdue University in robotics development.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Video games often use motion capture to animate athletes, martial artists, and other in-game characters.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] As early as 1988, an early form of motion capture was used to animate the 2D player characters of Martech's video game *Vixen* (performed by model Corinne Russell) and Magical Company's 2D arcade fighting game *Last Apostle Puppet Show* (to animate digitized sprites).
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Motion capture was later notably used to animate the 3D character models in the Sega Model arcade games *Virtua Fighter* (1993) and *Virtua Fighter 2* (1994).
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In mid-1995, developer/publisher Acclaim Entertainment had its own in-house motion capture studio built into its headquarters.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Namco's 1995 arcade game *Soul Edge* used passive optical system markers for motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Motion capture also uses athletes in based-off animated games, such as Naughty Dog's Crash Bandicoot, Insomniac Games' Spyro the Dragon, and Rare's Dinosaur Planet.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Indoor positioning is another application for optical motion capture systems.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Robotics researchers often use motion capture systems when developing and evaluating control, estimation, and perception algorithms and hardware.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In outdoor spaces, it's possible to achieve accuracy to the centimeter by using the Global Navigation Satellite System (GNSS) together with Real-Time Kinematics (RTK).
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] However, this reduces significantly when there is no line-of-sight to the satellites — such as in indoor environments.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The majority of vendors selling commercial optical motion capture systems provide accessible open source drivers that integrate with the popular Robotic Operating System (ROS) framework, allowing researchers and developers to effectively test their robots during development.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In the field of aerial robotics research, motion capture systems are widely used for positioning as well.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Regulations on airspace usage limit how feasible outdoor experiments can be conducted with Unmanned Aerial Systems (UAS).
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Indoor tests can circumvent such restrictions.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Many labs and institutions around the world have built indoor motion capture volumes for this purpose.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Purdue University houses the world's largest indoor motion capture system, inside the Purdue UAS Research and Test (PURT) facility.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] PURT is dedicated to UAS research, and provides tracking volume of 600,000 cubic feet using 60 motion capture cameras.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The optical motion capture system is able to track targets in its volume with millimeter accuracy, effectively providing the true position of targets — the "ground truth" baseline in research and development.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Results derived from other sensors and algorithms can then be compared to the ground truth data to evaluate their performance.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Movies use motion capture for CGI effects, in some cases replacing traditional cel animation, and for completely CGI creatures, such as Gollum, The Mummy, King Kong, Davy Jones from *Pirates of the Caribbean*, the Na'vi from the film *Avatar*, and Clu from *Tron: Legacy*.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The Great Goblin, the three Stone-trolls, many of the orcs and goblins in the 2012 film *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey*, and Smaug were created using motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In the 1990 movie *Total Recall*, the sequence where Arnold Schwarzenegger and other actors walk through an X-ray machine was shot using motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The film *Batman Forever* (1995) used some motion capture for certain visual effects.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Warner Bros. had acquired motion capture technology from arcade video game company Acclaim Entertainment for use in the film's production.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Acclaim's 1995 video game of the same name also used the same motion capture technology to animate the digitized sprite graphics.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The 1999 film *Star Wars: Episode I – The Phantom Menace* was the first feature-length film to include a main character created (Jar Jar Binks, played by Ahmed Best), using motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The 2000 Indian-American film *Sinbad: Beyond the Veil of Mists* was the first feature-length film made primarily with motion capture, although many character animators also worked on the film, which had a very limited release.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] 2001's *Final Fantasy: The Spirits Within* was the first widely released movie to be made with motion capture technology.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Despite its poor box-office intake, supporters of motion capture technology took notice.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Storymind Entertainment, which is an independent Ukrainian studio, created a neo-noir third-person / shooter video game called *My Eyes On You*, using motion capture in order to animate its main character, Jordan Adalien, and along with non-playable characters.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Of the three nominees for the 2006 Academy Award for Best Animated Feature, two of the nominees (*Monster House* and the winner *Happy Feet*) used motion capture, and only Disney**·**Pixar's *Cars* was animated without it.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Since 2001, motion capture has been used extensively to simulate or approximate the look of live-action theater, with nearly photorealistic digital character models.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] *The Polar Express* used motion capture to allow Tom Hanks to perform as several distinct digital characters (in which he also provided the voices).
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The 2007 adaptation of the saga *Beowulf* animated digital characters whose appearances were based in part on the actors who provided their motions and voices.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] James Cameron's highly popular *Avatar* used this technique to create the Na'vi that inhabit Pandora.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The Walt Disney Company has produced Robert Zemeckis's *A Christmas Carol* using this technique.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In 2007, Disney acquired Zemeckis' ImageMovers Digital (that produces motion capture films), but then closed it in 2011, after a box office failure of *Mars Needs Moms*.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Television series produced entirely with motion capture animation include *Laflaque* in Canada, *Sprookjesboom* and *Cafe de Wereld* in The Netherlands, and *Headcases* in the UK.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Virtual reality and augmented reality providers, such as uSens and Gestigon, allow users to interact with digital content in real time by capturing hand motions.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This can be useful for training simulations, visual perception tests, or performing virtual walk-throughs in a 3D environment.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Motion capture technology is frequently used in digital puppetry systems to drive computer-generated characters in real time.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Gait analysis is one application of motion capture in clinical medicine.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Techniques allow clinicians to evaluate human motion across several biomechanical factors, often while streaming this information live into analytical software.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] One innovative use is pose detection, which can empower patients during post-surgical recovery or rehabilitation after injuries.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This approach enables continuous monitoring, real-time guidance, and individually tailored programs to enhance patient outcomes.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Some physical therapy clinics utilize motion capture as an objective way to quantify patient progress.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This method allowed views and angles not possible from a pre-rendered animation.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Cameron was so proud of his results that he invited Steven Spielberg and George Lucas on set to view the system in action.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In Marvel's *The Avengers*, Mark Ruffalo used motion capture so he could play his character the Hulk, rather than have him be only CGI as in previous films, making Ruffalo the first actor to play both the human and the Hulk versions of Bruce Banner.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] FaceRig software uses facial recognition technology from ULSee.Inc to map a player's facial expressions and the body tracking technology from Perception Neuron to map the body movement onto a 2D or 3D character's motion on-screen.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] During *Game Developers Conference* 2016 in San Francisco *Epic Games* demonstrated full-body motion capture live in Unreal Engine.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The whole scene, from the upcoming game *Hellblade* about a woman warrior named Senua, was rendered in real-time.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The keynote was a collaboration between *Unreal Engine*, *Ninja Theory*, *3Lateral*, *Cubic Motion*, *IKinema* and *Xsens*.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In 2020, the two-time Olympic figure skating champion Yuzuru Hanyu graduated from Waseda University.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In his thesis, using data provided by 31 sensors placed on his body, he analysed his jumps.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] He evaluated the use of technology both in order to improve the scoring system and to help skaters improve their jumping technique.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In March 2021 a summary of the thesis was published in the academic journal.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Motion tracking or motion capture started as a photogrammetric analysis tool in biomechanics research in the 1970s and 1980s, and expanded into education, training, sports and recently computer animation for television, cinema, and video games as the technology matured.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Since the 20th century, the performer has to wear markers near each joint to identify the motion by the positions or angles between the markers.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Acoustic, inertial, LED, magnetic or reflective markers, or combinations of any of these, are tracked, optimally at least two times the frequency rate of the desired motion.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The resolution of the system is important in both the spatial resolution and temporal resolution as motion blur causes almost the same problems as low resolution.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Since the beginning of the 21st century - and because of the rapid growth of technology - new methods have been developed.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Most modern systems can extract the silhouette of the performer from the background.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Afterwards all joint angles are calculated by fitting in a mathematical model into the silhouette.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] For movements you can not see a change of the silhouette, there are hybrid systems available that can do both (marker and silhouette), but with less marker.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In robotics, some motion capture systems are based on simultaneous localization and mapping.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The centroid of the marker is estimated as a position within the two-dimensional image that is captured.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The grayscale value of each pixel can be used to provide sub-pixel accuracy by finding the centroid of the Gaussian.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] An object with markers attached at known positions is used to calibrate the cameras and obtain their positions, and the lens distortion of each camera is measured.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] If two calibrated cameras see a marker, a three-dimensional fix can be obtained.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Typically a system will consist of around 2 to 48 cameras.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Systems of over three hundred cameras exist to try to reduce marker swap.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Extra cameras are required for full coverage around the capture subject and multiple subjects.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Vendors have constraint software to reduce the problem of marker swapping since all passive markers appear identical.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Unlike active marker systems and magnetic systems, passive systems do not require the user to wear wires or electronic equipment.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Instead, hundreds of rubber balls are attached with reflective tape, which needs to be replaced periodically.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The markers are usually attached directly to the skin (as in biomechanics), or they are velcroed to a performer wearing a full-body spandex/lycra suit designed specifically for motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This type of system can capture large numbers of markers at frame rates usually around 120 to 160 fps although by lowering the resolution and tracking a smaller region of interest they can track as high as 10,000 fps.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Active optical systems triangulate positions by illuminating one LED at a time very quickly or multiple LEDs with software to identify them by their relative positions, somewhat akin to celestial navigation.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Rather than reflecting light back that is generated externally, the markers themselves are powered to emit their own light.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Since the inverse square law provides one quarter of the power at two times the distance, this can increase the distances and volume for capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This also enables a high signal-to-noise ratio, resulting in very low marker jitter and a resulting high measurement resolution (often down to 0.1 mm within the calibrated volume).
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The TV series *Stargate SG1* produced episodes using an active optical system for the VFX allowing the actor to walk around props that would make motion capture difficult for other non-active optical systems.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] ILM used active markers in *Van Helsing* to allow capture of Dracula's flying brides on very large sets similar to Weta's use of active markers in *Rise of the Planet of the Apes*.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The power to each marker can be provided sequentially in phase with the capture system providing a unique identification of each marker for a given capture frame at a cost to the resultant frame rate.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The ability to identify each marker in this manner is useful in real-time applications.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The alternative method of identifying markers is to do it algorithmically requiring extra processing of the data.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] There are also possibilities to find the position by using colored LED markers.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In these systems, each color is assigned to a specific point of the body.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] One of the earliest active marker systems in the 1980s was a hybrid passive-active mocap system with rotating mirrors and colored glass reflective markers and which used masked linear array detectors.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Active marker systems can further be refined by strobing one marker on at a time, or tracking multiple markers over time and modulating the amplitude or pulse width to provide marker ID.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] 12-megapixel spatial resolution modulated systems show more subtle movements than 4-megapixel optical systems by having both higher spatial and temporal resolution.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Directors can see the actor's performance in real-time, and watch the results on the motion capture-driven CG character.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The unique marker IDs reduce the turnaround, by eliminating marker swapping and providing much cleaner data than other technologies.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] LEDs with onboard processing and radio synchronization allow motion capture outdoors in direct sunlight while capturing at 120 to 960 frames per second due to a high-speed electronic shutter.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Computer processing of modulated IDs allows less hand cleanup or filtered results for lower operational costs.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This higher accuracy and resolution requires more processing than passive technologies, but the additional processing is done at the camera to improve resolution via subpixel or centroid processing, providing both high resolution and high speed.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These motion capture systems typically cost $20,000 for an eight-camera, 12-megapixel spatial resolution 120-hertz system with one actor.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] One can reverse the traditional approach based on high-speed cameras.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Systems such as Prakash use inexpensive multi-LED high-speed projectors.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The specially built multi-LED IR projectors optically encode the space.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Instead of retro-reflective or active light emitting diode (LED) markers, the system uses photosensitive marker tags to decode the optical signals.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] By attaching tags with photo sensors to scene points, the tags can compute not only their own locations of each point, but also their own orientation, incident illumination, and reflectance.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These tracking tags work in natural lighting conditions and can be imperceptibly embedded in attire or other objects.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The system supports an unlimited number of tags in a scene, with each tag uniquely identified to eliminate marker reacquisition issues.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Since the system eliminates a high-speed camera and the corresponding high-speed image stream, it requires significantly lower data bandwidth.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The tags also provide incident illumination data which can be used to match scene lighting when inserting synthetic elements.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The technique appears ideal for on-set motion capture or real-time broadcasting of virtual sets but has yet to be proven.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Motion capture technology has been available for researchers and scientists for a few decades, which has given new insight into many fields.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The vital part of the system, the underwater camera, has a waterproof housing.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The housing has a finish that withstands corrosion and chlorine which makes it perfect for use in basins and swimming pools.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Industrial high-speed cameras can also be used as infrared cameras.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Infrared underwater cameras come with a cyan light strobe instead of the typical IR light for minimum fall-off underwater and high-speed cameras with an LED light or with the option of using image processing.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] An underwater camera is typically able to measure 15–20 meters depending on the water quality, the camera and the type of marker used.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Unsurprisingly, the best range is achieved when the water is clear, and like always, the measurement volume is also dependent on the number of cameras.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] A range of underwater markers are available for different circumstances.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Different pools require different mountings and fixtures.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Therefore, all underwater motion capture systems are uniquely tailored to suit each specific pool instalment.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] For cameras placed in the center of the pool, specially designed tripods, using suction cups, are provided.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Emerging techniques and research in computer vision are leading to the rapid development of the markerless approach to motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Markerless systems such as those developed at Stanford University, the University of Maryland, MIT, and the Max Planck Institute, do not require subjects to wear special equipment for tracking.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Special computer algorithms are designed to allow the system to analyze multiple streams of optical input and identify human forms, breaking them down into constituent parts for tracking.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Traditionally markerless optical motion tracking is used to keep track of various objects, including airplanes, launch vehicles, missiles and satellites.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Many such optical motion tracking applications occur outdoors, requiring differing lens and camera configurations.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] High-resolution images of the target being tracked can thereby provide more information than just motion data.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The image obtained from NASA's long-range tracking system on the space shuttle Challenger's fatal launch provided crucial evidence about the cause of the accident.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Optical tracking systems are also used to identify known spacecraft and space debris despite the fact that it has a disadvantage compared to radar in that the objects must be reflecting or emitting sufficient light.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] An optical tracking system typically consists of three subsystems: the optical imaging system, the mechanical tracking platform and the tracking computer.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The optical imaging system is responsible for converting the light from the target area into a digital image that the tracking computer can process.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Depending on the design of the optical tracking system, the optical imaging system can vary from as simple as a standard digital camera to as specialized as an astronomical telescope on the top of a mountain.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The specification of the optical imaging system determines the upper limit of the effective range of the tracking system.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The mechanical tracking platform holds the optical imaging system and is responsible for manipulating the optical imaging system in such a way that it always points to the target being tracked.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The dynamics of the mechanical tracking platform combined with the optical imaging system determines the tracking system's ability to keep the lock on a target that changes speed rapidly.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The tracking computer is responsible for capturing the images from the optical imaging system, analyzing the image to extract the target position and controlling the mechanical tracking platform to follow the target.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] First, the tracking computer has to be able to capture the image at a relatively high frame rate.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This posts a requirement on the bandwidth of the image-capturing hardware.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The second challenge is that the image processing software has to be able to extract the target image from its background and calculate its position.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Several textbook image-processing algorithms are designed for this task.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This problem can be simplified if the tracking system can expect certain characteristics that is common in all the targets it will track.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The next problem down the line is controlling the tracking platform to follow the target.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This is a typical control system design problem rather than a challenge, which involves modeling the system dynamics and designing controllers to control it.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This will however become a challenge if the tracking platform the system has to work with is not designed for real-time.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The software that runs such systems is also customized for the corresponding hardware components.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] One example of such software is OpticTracker, which controls computerized telescopes to track moving objects at great distances, such as planes and satellites.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Another option is the software SimiShape, which can also be used hybrid in combination with markers.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] RGB-D cameras such as Kinect capture both the color and depth images.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] By fusing the two images, 3D colored voxels can be captured, allowing motion capture of 3D human motion and human surface in real-time.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Because of the use of a single-view camera, motions captured are usually noisy.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Machine learning techniques have been proposed to automatically reconstruct such noisy motions into higher quality ones, using methods such as lazy learning and Gaussian models.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Such method generates accurate enough motion for serious applications like ergonomic assessment.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Inertial motion capture technology is based on miniature inertial sensors, biomechanical models and sensor fusion algorithms.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The motion data of the inertial sensors (inertial guidance system) is often transmitted wirelessly to a computer, where the motion is recorded or viewed.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Most inertial systems use inertial measurement units (IMUs) containing a combination of gyroscope, magnetometer, and accelerometer, to measure rotational rates.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These rotations are translated to a skeleton in the software.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Much like optical markers, the more IMU sensors the more natural the data.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] No external cameras, emitters or markers are needed for relative motions, although they are required to give the absolute position of the user if desired.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Inertial motion capture systems capture the full six degrees of freedom body motion of a human in real-time and can give limited direction information if they include a magnetic bearing sensor, although these are much lower resolution and susceptible to electromagnetic noise.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Benefits of using Inertial systems include: capturing in a variety of environments including tight spaces, no solving, portability, and large capture areas.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Disadvantages include lower positional accuracy and positional drift which can compound over time.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These systems are similar to the Wii controllers but are more sensitive and have greater resolution and update rates.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] They can accurately measure the direction to the ground to within a degree.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The popularity of inertial systems is rising amongst game developers, mainly because of the quick and easy setup resulting in a fast pipeline.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] A range of suits are now available from various manufacturers and base prices range from $1000 to US$80,000.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Mechanical motion capture systems directly track body joint angles and are often referred to as exoskeleton motion capture systems, due to the way the sensors are attached to the body.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] A performer attaches the skeletal-like structure to their body and as they move so do the articulated mechanical parts, measuring the performer's relative motion.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Mechanical motion capture systems are real-time, relatively low-cost, free from occlusion, and wireless (untethered) systems that have unlimited capture volume.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Typically, they are rigid structures of jointed, straight metal or plastic rods linked together with potentiometers that articulate at the joints of the body.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These suits tend to be in the $25,000 to $75,000 range plus an external absolute positioning system.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Some suits provide limited force feedback or haptic input.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Magnetic systems calculate position and orientation by the relative magnetic flux of three orthogonal coils on both the transmitter and each receiver.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The relative intensity of the voltage or current of the three coils allows these systems to calculate both range and orientation by meticulously mapping the tracking volume.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The sensor output is six degrees of freedom (6DOF), which provides useful results obtained with two-thirds the number of markers required in optical systems; one on upper arm and one on lower arm for elbow position and angle.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The markers are vulnerable to magnetic and electrical interference from metal objects in the environment, like rebar (steel reinforcing bars in concrete) or wiring, which affect the magnetic field, and electrical sources such as monitors, lights, cables and computers.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The sensor response is nonlinear, especially toward edges of the capture area.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The wiring from the sensors tends to preclude extreme performance movements.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] With magnetic systems, it is possible to monitor the results of a motion capture session in real time.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The capture volumes for magnetic systems are dramatically smaller than they are for optical systems.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] With the magnetic systems, there is a distinction between alternating-current (AC) and direct-current (DC) systems: DC system uses square pulses, AC systems use sine waves.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Stretch sensors are flexible parallel plate capacitors that measure either stretch, bend, shear, or pressure and are typically produced from silicone.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] When the sensor stretches or squeezes its capacitance value changes.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] This data can be transmitted via Bluetooth or direct input and used to detect minute changes in body motion.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Stretch sensors are unaffected by magnetic interference and are free from occlusion.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The stretchable nature of the sensors also means they do not suffer from positional drift, which is common with inertial systems.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Stretchable sensors, on the other hands, due to the material properties of their substrates and conducting materials, suffer from relatively low signal-to-noise ratio, requiring filtering or machine learning to make them usable for motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These solutions result in higher latency when compared to alternative sensors.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Most traditional motion capture hardware vendors provide for some type of low-resolution facial capture utilizing anywhere from 32 to 300 markers with either an active or passive marker system.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] All of these solutions are limited by the time it takes to apply the markers, calibrate the positions and process the data.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Ultimately the technology also limits their resolution and raw output quality levels.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] High-fidelity facial motion capture, also known as **performance capture**, is the next generation of fidelity and is utilized to record the more complex movements in a human face in order to capture higher degrees of emotion.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Facial capture is currently arranging itself in several distinct camps, including traditional motion capture data, blend-shaped based solutions, capturing the actual topology of an actor's face, and proprietary systems.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] These techniques tend to be only limited in feature resolution by the camera resolution, apparent object size and number of cameras.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] If the user's face is 50 percent of the working area of the camera and a camera has megapixel resolution, then sub millimeter facial motions can be detected by comparing frames.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Recent work is focusing on increasing the frame rates and doing optical flow to allow the motions to be retargeted to other computer generated faces, rather than just making a 3D Mesh of the actor and their expressions.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Radio frequency positioning systems are becoming more viable as higher frequency radio frequency devices allow greater precision than older technologies such as radar.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The speed of light is 30 centimeters per nanosecond (billionth of a second), so a 10 gigahertz (billion cycles per second) radio frequency signal enables an accuracy of about 3 centimeters.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] By measuring amplitude to a quarter wavelength, it is possible to improve the resolution down to about 8 mm.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] To achieve the resolution of optical systems, frequencies of 50 gigahertz or higher are needed, which are almost as dependent on line of sight and as easy to block as optical systems.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Multipath and reradiation of the signal are likely to cause additional problems, but these technologies will be ideal for tracking larger volumes with reasonable accuracy, since the required resolution at 100 meter distances is not likely to be as high.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Many scientists believe that radio frequency will never produce the accuracy required for motion capture.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Researchers at Massachusetts Institute of Technology researchers said in 2015 that they had made a system that tracks motion by radio frequency signals.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] An alternative approach was developed where the actor is given an unlimited walking area through the use of a rotating sphere, similar to a hamster ball, which contains internal sensors recording the angular movements, removing the need for external cameras and other equipment.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Even though this technology could potentially lead to much lower costs for motion capture, the basic sphere is only capable of recording a single continuous direction.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Additional sensors worn on the person would be needed to record anything more.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Another alternative is using a 6DOF (Degrees of freedom) motion platform with an integrated omni-directional treadmill with high resolution optical motion capture to achieve the same effect.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] The captured person can walk in an unlimited area, negotiating different uneven terrains.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] Applications include medical rehabilitation for balance training, bio-mechanical research and virtual reality.
[src:skeletal-animation/motion-capture] In 3D pose estimation, an actor's pose can be reconstructed from an image or depth map.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] In 3D computer graphics and solid modeling, a **polygon mesh** is a collection of **vertices**, **edges** and **faces** that define the shape of a polyhedral object's surface.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] It simplifies rendering, as in a wire-frame model.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The faces usually consist of triangles (triangle mesh), quadrilaterals (quads), or other simple convex polygons (n-gons).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] A polygonal mesh may also be more generally composed of concave polygons, or even polygons with holes.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The study of polygon meshes is a large sub-field of computer graphics (specifically 3D computer graphics) and geometric modeling.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Different representations of polygon meshes are used for different applications and goals.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The variety of operations performed on meshes includes Boolean logic (Constructive solid geometry), smoothing, and simplification.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Algorithms also exist for ray tracing, collision detection, and rigid-body dynamics with polygon meshes.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] If the mesh's edges are rendered instead of the faces, then the model becomes a wireframe model.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Several methods exist for mesh generation, including the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Volumetric meshes are distinct from polygon meshes in that they explicitly represent both the surface and interior region of a structure, while polygon meshes only explicitly represent the surface (the volume is implicit).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Objects created with polygon meshes must store different types of elements.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] These include vertices, edges, faces, polygons and surfaces.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] In many applications, only vertices, edges and either faces or polygons are stored.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] A renderer may support only 3-sided faces, so polygons must be constructed of many of these, as shown above.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] However, many renderers either support quads and higher-sided polygons, or are able to convert polygons to triangles on the fly, making it unnecessary to store a mesh in a triangulated form.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] A vertex in computer graphics terms is a data structure that describes the position of a point in 2, 3 or 4D space on a surface along with optional attributes - other values used to render the object correctly.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Most attributes of a vertex represent vectors in the space to be rendered.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] These vectors are typically 2 (*x, y*) or 3 (*x, y, z*) dimensional and can include a fourth homogeneous coordinate (*w*)..
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] In real-time rendering these properties are used by a vertex shader or vertex pipeline.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Attributes can include position, color, reflectance, specularity, texture mapping coordinates, normal vectors, and displacement mapping.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Polygon meshes may be represented in a variety of ways, using different methods to store the vertex, edge and face data.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Each representation has advantages and disadvantages, discussed in Smith (2006).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of vertices connected to other vertices.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] This is the simplest representation, but not widely used since the face and edge information is implicit.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Thus, it is necessary to traverse the data in order to generate a list of faces for rendering.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] In addition, operations on edges and faces are not easily accomplished.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] However, VV meshes benefit from small storage space and efficient morphing of shape.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows a four-sided box as represented by a VV mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Each vertex indexes its neighboring vertices.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The last two vertices, 8 and 9 at the top and bottom center of the "box-cylinder", have four connected vertices rather than five.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] A general system must be able to handle an arbitrary number of vertices connected to any given vertex.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] For a complete description of VV meshes see Smith (2006).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes represent an object as a set of faces and a set of vertices.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] This is the most widely used mesh representation, being the input typically accepted by modern graphics hardware.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Face-vertex meshes improve on VV mesh for modelling in that they allow explicit lookup of the vertices of a face, and the faces surrounding a vertex.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" example as an FV mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Vertex v5 is highlighted to show the faces that surround it.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Notice that, in this example, every face is required to have exactly 3 vertices.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] However, this does not mean every vertex has the same number of surrounding faces.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] For rendering, the face list is usually transmitted to the GPU as a set of indices to vertices, and the vertices are sent as position/color/normal structures (in the figure, only position is given).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] This has the benefit that changes in shape, but not geometry, can be dynamically updated by simply resending the vertex data without updating the face connectivity.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Modelling requires easy traversal of all structures.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] With face-vertex meshes it is easy to find the vertices of a face.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Also, the vertex list contains a list of faces connected to each vertex.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Unlike VV meshes, both faces and vertices are explicit, so locating neighboring faces and vertices is constant time.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] However, the edges are implicit, so a search is still needed to find all the faces surrounding a given face.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Other dynamic operations, such as splitting or merging a face, are also difficult with face-vertex meshes.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Introduced by Baumgart in 1975, winged-edge meshes explicitly represent the vertices, faces, and edges of a mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] This representation is widely used in modelling programs to provide the greatest flexibility in dynamically changing the mesh geometry, because split and merge operations can be done quickly.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Their primary drawback is large storage requirements and increased complexity due to maintaining many indices.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] A good discussion of implementation issues of Winged-edge meshes may be found in the book *Graphics Gems II*.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes address the issue of traversing from edge to edge, and providing an ordered set of faces around an edge.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] For any given edge, the number of outgoing edges may be arbitrary.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] To simplify this, winged-edge meshes provide only four, the nearest clockwise and counter-clockwise edges at each end.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The other edges may be traversed incrementally.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The information for each edge therefore resembles a butterfly, hence "winged-edge" meshes.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The above figure shows the "box-cylinder" as a winged-edge mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The total data for an edge consists of 2 vertices (endpoints), 2 faces (on each side), and 4 edges (winged-edge).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Rendering of winged-edge meshes for graphics hardware requires generating a face index list, which is usually done only when the geometry changes.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are ideally suited for dynamic geometry, such as subdivision surfaces and interactive modelling, since changes to the mesh can occur locally.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Traversal across the mesh, as might be needed for collision detection, can be accomplished efficiently.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes are not the only representation which allows for dynamic changes to geometry.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] A representation which combines winged-edge meshes and face-vertex meshes is the render dynamic mesh (RDM), which explicitly stores both, the vertices of a face and faces of a vertex (like FV meshes), and the faces and vertices of an edge (like winged-edge).
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] RDM's require less storage space than standard winged-edge meshes, and can be directly rendered by graphics hardware since the face list contains an index of vertices.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] In addition, traversal from vertex to face is explicit (constant time), as is from face to vertex.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] RDM's do not require the four outgoing edges since these can be found by traversing from edge to face, then face to neighboring edge.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] RDM's benefit from the features of winged-edge meshes by allowing for geometry to be dynamically updated.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] See Tobler & Maierhofer (WSCG 2006) for more details.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The notation *avg(V,V)* means the average number of vertices connected to a given vertex; *avg(E,V)* means the average number of edges connected to a given vertex, and *avg(F,V)* is the average number of faces connected to a given vertex.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The notation "V → f1, f2, f3, ... → v1, v2, v3, ..." describes that a traversal across multiple elements is required to perform the operation.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] For example, to get "all vertices around a given vertex V" using the face-vertex mesh, it is necessary to first find the faces around the given vertex V using the vertex list.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Then, from those faces, use the face list to find the vertices around them.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge meshes explicitly store nearly all information, and other operations always traverse to the edge first to get additional info.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are the only representation that explicitly stores the neighboring vertices of a given vertex.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] As the mesh representations become more complex (from left to right in the summary), the amount of information explicitly stored increases.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] This gives more direct, constant time, access to traversal and topology of various elements but at the cost of increased overhead and space in maintaining indices properly.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] As a general rule, face-vertex meshes are used whenever an object must be rendered on graphics hardware that does not change geometry (connectivity), but may deform or morph shape (vertex positions) such as real-time rendering of static or morphing objects.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Winged-edge or render dynamic meshes are used when the geometry changes, such as in interactive modeling packages or for computing subdivision surfaces.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Vertex-vertex meshes are ideal for efficient, complex changes in geometry or topology so long as hardware rendering is not of concern.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes store faces in an ordered, yet independent, way so that the mesh can be transmitted in pieces.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] The order of faces may be spatial, spectral, or based on other properties of the mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Streaming meshes allow a very large mesh to be rendered even while it is still being loaded.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Progressive meshes transmit the vertex and face data with increasing levels of detail.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Unlike *streaming meshes*, progressive meshes give the overall shape of the entire object, but at a low level of detail.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Additional data, new edges and faces, progressively increase the detail of the mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes transmit progressive changes to a mesh as a set of normal displacements from a base mesh.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] With this technique, a series of textures represent the desired incremental modifications.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Normal meshes are compact, since only a single scalar value is needed to express displacement.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] However, the technique requires a complex series of transformations to create the displacement textures.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] There exist many different file formats for storing polygon mesh data.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Each format is most effective when used for the purpose intended by its creator.
[src:skeletal-animation/polygon-mesh] Popular formats include .fbx, .dae, .obj, and .stl.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] The technique was introduced in 1988 by Nadia Magnenat Thalmann, Richard Laperrière, and Daniel Thalmann.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] This technique is used in virtually all animation systems where simplified user interfaces allow animators to control often complex algorithms and a huge amount of geometry; most notably through inverse kinematics and other "goal-oriented" techniques.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] This technique constructs a series of bones (which need not correspond to any real-world anatomical feature), sometimes also referred to as rigging in the noun sense.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Each bone has a three-dimensional transformation from the default bind pose (which includes its position, scale and orientation), and an optional parent bone.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] The full transform of a child node is the product of its parent transform and its own transform.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] So moving a thigh-bone will move the lower leg too.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] As the character is animated, the bones change their transformation over time, under the influence of some animation controller.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] A rig is generally composed of both forward kinematics and inverse kinematics parts that may interact with each other.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Skeletal animation is referring to the forward kinematics part of the rig, where a complete set of bone configurations identifies a unique pose.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Each bone in the skeleton is associated with some portion of the character's visual representation (the mesh) in a process called skinning.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] In the most common case of a polygonal mesh character, the bone is associated with a group of vertices; for example, in a model of a human being, the bone for the thigh would be associated with the vertices making up the polygons in the model's thigh.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Portions of the character's skin can normally be associated with multiple bones, each one having a scaling factor called vertex weights, or blend weights.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] The movement of skin near the joints of two bones, can therefore be influenced by both bones.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] In most state-of-the-art graphical engines, the skinning process is done on the GPU by a shader program.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] For a polygonal mesh, each vertex can have a blend weight for each bone.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] To calculate the final position of the vertex, a transformation matrix is created for each bone which, when applied to the vertex, first puts the vertex in bone space then puts it back into mesh space.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] After applying a matrix to the vertex, it is scaled by its corresponding weight.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] This algorithm is called matrix-palette skinning or linear-blend skinning, because the set of bone transformations (stored as transform matrices) form a palette for the skin vertex to choose from.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Skeletal animation is the standard way to animate characters or mechanical objects for a prolonged period of time.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] It is commonly used by video game artists and in the film industry, and can also be applied to mechanical objects and any other objects made up of rigid elements and joints.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Performance capture (or motion capture) can speed up the process of skeletal animation, as well as increasing the level of realism.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Rigs may be driven by ragdoll physics which automatically calculate physics of motion and resistance with skeletal frames.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Virtual anatomy properties such as weight of limbs, muscle reaction, bone strength, and joint constraints may be added for realistic bouncing, buckling, fracture, and tumbling effects.
[src:skeletal-animation/skeletal-animation] Some popular software packages within which rigs may be created include Blender, Autodesk Maya, SideFX Houdini, Autodesk 3ds Max, Maxon Cinema 4D, Unreal Engine, and many others.
